ng World, An Absent God: Midrash, Hermeneutics, and Relational Psychoanalysis -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Jewish tradition, it is incumbent upon every generation to attempt to find meaning in its history. Meaning is co-created within the context of the inter-subjective field of a meeting of minds. Psychoanalysis, in some respects like the Jewish tradition from which it emerged, represents a body of thought about man’s relation to himself and to others, and places great value on the influence of memory, narrative, and history in creating meaning within the dyadic relationship of analyst and patient. In Answering a Question with a Question: Contemporary Psychoanalysis and Jewish Thought, editors Aron and Henik have brought together an international collection of contemporary scholars and clinicians to address the interface and the mutual influence of Jewish thought and modern psychoanalysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJewish philosophy. 0aJudaism. 0aPsychoanalysis and culture. 0aPsychoanalysis and religion. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh1 aArnowitz, Yehoshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAron, Lewis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAron, Lewis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAronson, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrickman, Celia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCushman, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrosh, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab